# Introduction

This document will discuss how Dynatrace detects problems and then sends alerts based on detected problems. The summary below is a general overview of the topics discussed in this document. The important terms section reviews terms that are discussed often in this document.

NOTE: This document is not official Dynatrace documentation and is not updated as such, so certain statements and/or screenshots may be out of date. This document is meant to supplement and clarify the official [documentation](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs).

**Last updated 11/20/2023**

***

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Summary of Detection and Alerting Process

In Dynatrace, there are four major components/steps with which problem detection and alerting can be configured; anomaly detection, alerting profiles, problem notifications, and maintenance windows. This section will give a brief summary of how a problem is processed over the problem lifecycle by these configurable components.

The problem lifecycle begins with anomaly detection. Dynatrace’s AI is continually monitoring the environment for metric anomalies. When an anomaly is detected, a Problem is opened. Anomaly detection settings can be used to tweak how sensitive the AI is to changes in the environment, thereby tweaking how often problems will be generated. These settings can be changed globally with the option to override the global settings or on an entity-by-entity basis. Host Groups also have their own override option for anomaly detection at the host level.

Once a problem has opened, Alerting Profiles come in to play. Alerting Profiles are configured to use a set of information from a problem to determine if an alert should be generated. Problem severity (the type of problem), impacted entity tags, and problem duration can all be configured to be used as conditions that must be fulfilled before an alert can be generated.

Once the conditions of an alerting profile are met, a problem notification (alert) can be sent. When an alerting profile is assigned to a Problem Notification configuration, any problems that fulfill the conditions of the assigned Alerting Profile will be alerted upon using the configurations made in the Problem Notification setting. Problem Notifications control the delivery method of an alert as well as the recipients, subject, and in some cases, the content of the sent message.

## Important Terms

**Entity** – An individual object entry in Dynatrace, such as a given host, service, or application

**Anomaly** – A scenario when a performance metric is outside of its baseline

**Problem** – A collection of information regarding one or more related anomalies in the Dynatrace environment

**Alert** – A notification regarding a specific problem sent from Dynatrace to some external recipient via methods such as email or external tool integration

**Anomaly Detection** – Configuration that determines if a metric is outside its baseline, consequently determining if a problem should be opened or not

**Alerting Profile** – Configuration that determines if and when an alert should be generated based on an open problem

**Problem Notifications** – Configuration that determines who receives an alert, how the alert is sent, and what content the alert contains

**Maintenance Windows** – Configuration that allows for the suppression of problems and/or alerts during designated time frames

**Tag** – Configurable labels or markers that add information to/about an applicable entity

**Management Zone** – A configurable logical division of the Dynatrace environment, based on some logical condition or business rule

# Anomaly Detection

A problem in Dynatrace begins with a when a metric exceeds its baseline by a configurable amount. This scenario is seen by Dynatrace as an anomaly. Anomaly detection settings within Dynatrace allow administrators to tweak anomaly sensitivity.

***

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Global Anomaly Detection Settings - Entities

Global anomaly detection settings are accessed via the settings menu, available to users with administrator privileges. These settings are separated by entity type such as applications and services. Configurations made here will affect all matching entities in the Dynatrace environment. Each entity type has its own anomaly detection settings as different metrics are being captured at each level. 

To the right, you can see the entity-based options listed in the Global Anomaly Detection Settings menu. Each of these options control anomaly detection behavior for all entities of that type. 

Each entity type has a set of anomalies that they can detect. As shown below, there are switches to toggle on/off specific anomaly types such as traffic drops, failure rate increases, and performance degradations (slowdowns). If toggled on Dynatrace will detect problems of that anomaly type and will ignore them if toggled off. Along with the toggles are options to configure automatic or static threshold detection. When using the automatic option, you can configure the ranges used to detect specific types of problems. Using static thresholds will allow you to configure a fixed threshold that, when exceeded, will generate a problem. Another option allows admins to suppress problem detection on services based on their request(s) per minute. This is to avoid over alerting on services that will be sensitive to anomaly detection due to low load.

As an example of how anomaly detection settings can be tweaked, we will use Service response time degradations. Below is a screenshot of the options available for the “response time degradation” anomaly type.

In this example Dynatrace **will** detect response time degradations using automatic settings. The automatic settings are configured to detect problems when the average response time increases by 100 milliseconds or more AND by 50% or more. Similarly, Dynatrace will generate a problem if the average response time of the slowest 10% of requests increases by 1000 milliseconds or more AND by 100% or more. In either individual case, BOTH conditions must be met for an alert to be generated. Along with this there is the option to suppress alerting on low traffic services, in this case any service with less than 15 requests per minute will not generate problems regardless of anomalies detected.

tiles.markdown:
## Global Anomaly Detection Settings – Mobile & Custom App 
Crash Rate Detection
Crash rate increase settings allow administrators to adjust the details that Dynatrace uses to detect crash rate increases. Crash rate detection settings for mobile applications can be found under **Settings > Anomaly detection > Mobile apps – Crash rate increase** and crash rate detection settings for custom applications can be found under **Settings > Anomaly detection > Custom apps – Crash rate increase**. When utilizing automatic settings, you can adjust the relative threshold, minimum number of active users, and detection sensitivity. Changing over to fixed thresholds limits options to an absolute threshold and minimum number of active users. Adjustments made here will act as the default for all mobile apps and custom apps respectively.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Global Anomaly Detection Settings - Extension Events

Extension event settings control anomaly detection for various extensions that can be used with Dynatrace. These settings can be accessed by administrators under **Settings > Anomaly detection > Extension events**. Extension events are toggled and configured on an event type basis, similarly to the entities above. Below is an example of what the Extension events screen displays when selected. As shown the events are listed with the event name, extension, on/off toggle, and edit options. Since every extension has it’s own set of events please refer to the individual documentation for a given extension for specific configuration instructions.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
***

## Global Anomaly Detection Settings – Metric Events
Metric event settings allow Dynatrace administrators to generate problems based on metric patterns not used by the Dynatrace AI out of the box. This configuration is found under **Settings > Anomaly Detection > Metric events**.

Configuration of custom events includes defining what metric will be used to trigger the event, applying filters to define the scope of entities to be monitored for the metric event, setting thresholds, and codifying resulting behavior. For an in-depth description of configuring metric events, please refer to the official [Metric Event documentation](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/platform/davis-ai/anomaly-detection/metric-events).


***

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Global Anomaly Detection Settings – Frequent Issue Detection

Frequent issue detection is a feature in Dynatrace that detects problems that appear to repeat in some pattern, designed to prevent overly noisy alerting. Dynatrace automatically detects frequent issues over a period of one week. A problem is automatically converted into a frequent issue if the problem is detected multiple times throughout the day over a week’s period and if it is not getting worse. Once classified as a frequent issue, alerting is automatically disabled. In the case that the frequent issue is getting worse, such as response time increasing more than normally observed, problem alerts will resume.

**This feature can only be toggled on/off globally** by topological entity level, as shown to the right.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
Lastly, Maintenance Window settings can be used to suppress problem detection and/or alerts during pre-configured timeframes. Maintenance Windows are configured by providing a scope and a time frame. If a problem pattern is impacting an entity within the provided scope during a configured time frame, resulting problems and/or alerts can be suppressed.

In short, all four of these settings (Anomaly Detection, Alerting Profiles, Problem Notifications, and Maintenance windows) can be configured to determine how problems are detected, how alerts are generated, who receives alerts, what alerts contain, and if alerts should be temporarily suppressed. These settings allow for detailed tuning of how Dynatrace will react in the event of irregular behavior detected in the environment. Above is a visual representation of how these configurations interact with each other.

## Individual Entity Anomaly Detection Settings
Dynatrace admins can override global settings on an entity-by-entity basis in order to tweak these settings to better fit the specific entity.

When viewing the entity page for any given Application, Service or Host an admin can select the settings option at the top right of the entity page, from here that entity’s settings page can be accessed. From here an admin can override the global anomaly detection settings and configure anomaly detection settings for that specific entity. The options displayed are the same set of options that are seen when configuring anomaly detection settings globally, but they are specific to the selected entity.

Hosts add another layer to this override mechanic with Host Groups. Admins can configure anomaly detection settings for Host Groups rather than individual hosts. In this way, admins can configure a whole group of hosts to use a standard set of anomaly detection settings based on that Host Group’s needs. From there individual hosts can be set to override their Host Group settings if needed. In short; global anomaly detection settings can be overridden by Host Group anomaly detection settings, which can be in turn overridden by Host anomaly detection settings.

***

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Service Failure Detection Settings
Another way to further tweak Dynatrace’s problem detection is through Service failure detection settings. These options are accessed by opening the settings for a given Service then navigating to Failure Detection. For any given service admins can configure ranges of http statuses as client or server errors via the HTTP parameters category. Under the general parameters category, admins can also tell Dynatrace which exceptions indicate client aborts, exceptions to ignore, custom handled exceptions, or create custom error rules.

# Alerting Profiles

When an anomaly is detected by the Dynatrace AI, a Problem is opened. Alerting profiles are used to determine what problems should be alerted on and when. Alerting profiles can be accessed by admins under **Settings > Alerting > Problem alerting profiles**.

***

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Management Zone Filter
Management Zones can be used to filter down applicable problems in a similar way as tags are used in severity rules. In Alerting Profiles admins can define which Management Zone the alerting profile applies to, such as shown to the right.

As shown, admins can select “All” Management Zones or an individual Management Zone. This will be used by the Alerting Profile to determine which problems apply to the Alerting Profile. If an entity impacted by the problem is included in the chosen Management Zone it will be eligible to be alerted upon by this Alerting Profile. If the “All” selection is chosen or if this option is left blank, no filter will be placed based on Management Zones.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
In this way admins can configure filters for the Alerting Profile in a similar way to how it works with tags on severity rules. Using Management Zones and Tags is also possible. A problem will be verified against the Management Zone filter first, then, if the problem still qualifies, it will be considered against any conditions placed on a severity rule, including tags. Using both Management Zones and tag conditions on severity rules together allows for greater granularity than either one configuration on its own.

Whether or not to use Management Zones as an Alerting Profile condition is up to admins to determine. It will come down to which approach works better for their environment. Using tags alone on severity rules helps control alert configurations but is very manual. Using tags allows for further granularity without having to make changes to the Management Zone. Management Zone filters are very good if Management Zones are well built out and conform to alerting needs. Management Zone filters are also very useful in large environments where one point of configuration helps keep manual configurations in check.

## Severity Rules

Alerting profiles use three pieces of data from a problem to determine whether a problem should be alerted upon or not. When combined these three considerations create a severity rule in an Alerting Profile. Severity rules are the key component of an alerting profile. An example of a severity rule is shown to the right.

The first piece of data used is the problem severity. Problem severity describes the type of problem that has been detected. When a problem is opened it is assigned a problem severity based on the anomaly pattern detected that caused the problem to open. Problem severity can hold one of the six following values; Availability, Error, Slowdown, Resource, Custom, Monitoring unavailable. Below are brief descriptions of each severity type.

- Availability - When important resources, such as hosts, processes that support services, or applications stop responding
- Error - When an application or service experiences a significant increase in error rate
- Slowdown - When the performance of an application, service, or database to significantly degrade is automatically classified
- Resource - When a shortage of a resource in your monitored environment is detected
- Custom – When a custom defined threshold has been breached
- Monitoring unavailable – When there has been an interruption to monitoring

The above example displays a severity rule that will only be considered if a problem has a Slowdown severity.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
Then, based on the problem severity, an Alerting Profile can be used to set a delay on any matching problem alerts. Admins can set alerts to be delayed based on how long a certain type of problem has been open. In the above example the Slowdown problem would have to remain open for more than 30 minutes before an alert would be generated. Inversely, if a slowdown type problem were to open and close without exceeding the 30-minute delay, no alert would be generated.

The final piece of data used by Alerting Profiles is tags. Tags can be used to filter down which problems apply to that Alerting Profile. When listed, an alert will only be generated if any one of the entities impacted by a problem contains the tag(s) listed.

There are two options in which tags can be utilized in a severity rule; “Only include entities that have all tags” or “Only include entities that have any tags. In the former option the rule will use AND logic in which all tags listed must be present on an impacted entity for the condition to be fulfilled. In the latter option the rule will use OR logic in which any one of the tags listed will fulfill the condition. In the example above the alerting condition will only be met if an impacted entity contains both the “EasyTravel” and “Production” tags.

All together the above severity rule states that an alert will only be generated if a slowdown problem that is impacting an entity tagged with both “EasyTravel” AND “Production” tags is open for 30 minutes or longer.

***

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Event Filters
Event Filters are used to further filter what is alerted upon in an Alerting Profile. Event Filters are used to specifically define which events should or should not be alerted on. 

As shown in the examples below, there are 3 configurable pieces to an Event Filter. The first piece is the event source, which can hold a value of “Predefined” or “Custom.” Selecting either of these will determine the options available for filtering out specific alerts. When “Predefined” is selected, a list of event types appears, allowing admins to filter on specific problem types, such as CPU saturation, failure rate increases, synthetic outages, etc. If “Custom” is selected, two toggle buttons appear. When toggled on, either button allows admins to filter problems based on their title or description, allowing for more granular, albeit manual, alert filters. Lastly, for any of the options there is the negate checkbox. When the checkbox is checked that will prevent any problems matching the pattern in the filter to be alerted upon, even if they meet the other criteria of the Alerting Profile. If left unchecked, only problems that match the event filter rule will be alerted upon, all others will be ignored by this alerting profile. When multiple event filters are used, they operate using or logic since a problem can only be of one type.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Alerting Profile Example

Using the example to the right, we will walk through how a problem runs through a fully configured alerting profile.
Assume there is an open problem in an environment with the following details

- The EasyTravel RUM application is experiencing a slowdown severity problem
- The EasyTravel app is tagged with both EasyTravel and Production
- This type of problem would be deemed as a “performance degradation”
- The problem has been open for 30 minutes

Now we will work our way through the Alerting Profile. The first condition that must be passed is the Management Zone filter. Since this alerting profile is configured to use All Management Zones this problem fulfills this condition. 

Next, we must look to find which severity rule applies to this specific problem. Since this is a slowdown problem, we will use the slowdown severity rule. Next, we must consider the duration of the problem. As this problem has been open for 30 minutes it fulfills the time duration condition for the slowdown alert rule. Next, we must make sure that the problem applies to the severity rules tag configurations. Even though it is not visible from the screenshot below, the slowdown rule being used requires that an impacted component must have BOTH the EasyTravel AND Production tags. (Note: The only way to tell if a severity rule is using AND or OR logic is to open the details for that rule, it cannot be determined from the overview). Since the impacted application is tagged with both required tags, the problem fulfills this requirement as well.

Lastly, we must check the problem against any configured Event Filters. For this alerting profile the only configured event filter is set to ignore problems with an event type of CPU saturation. Since the example problem is a performance degradation, it does not match this filter and will not be negated.

Since this problem passes all configured rules of this alerting profile, it will be alerted on. Below is the logic preview that dynatrace has provided for this alerting profile.

## Alerting Profiles Troubleshooting Tip

Dynatrace has a built-in way to determine if a problem has fulfilled the requirements of an alerting profile. 

When on the problems page, the **Filter by** bar has the option to filter by alerting profile. If an Alerting Profile filter is set, any problems that did not satisfy the requirements of that alerting profile will be filtered out. This allows you to determine if an alerting profile is working as expected. 

Note: this trick only displays problems that meet the requirements of an alerting profile. If a problem shows up with this filter applied, it does not necessarily mean that an alert was actually sent. If an alerting profile is not assigned to a Problem Notification, no alert will be sent, even if a problem meets the requirements of that alerting profile. Keep this in mind when troubleshooting Alerting Profiles.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
# Problem Notifications

The next configurable component of alerting functionalities within Dynatrace are problem notifications. Problem notifications are how Dynatrace sends alerts to recipients. As shown below, there are many integrations available to Dynatrace when it comes to sending out alerts. This section will focus solely on email notifications, for more details on a given integration please see the documentation for that integration. Problem notifications are found under **Settings > Integration > Problem notifications**. 

When a problem fulfills all the requirements in an alerting profile that problem can be alerted on. Problem Notifications are configured by admins so that generated alerts are sent to the correct people.

The first configuration made in a Problem Notification is to 1) set the display name. This is the name that is shown in the Dynatrace settings menu, so be sure to give it a descriptive name. It is best to come up with a naming convention so that it is easy to quickly find a desired Problem Notification configuration. The next configurations are 2) the recipients. Email notifications allow admins to configure both direct recipients as well as anyone who should be CC’d or BCC’d on the email notification. Next, admins 3) configure the subject and the body of the email. This can be done using static text or placeholders. The placeholders will be filled in with information from the problem when it is sent, allowing for dynamic messages. This section also includes a toggle that determines if a separate email is sent when the Problem closes. The last configuration made is 4) assigning an Alerting Profile to that Notification set. 

Any problems that fulfill the conditions of the assigned Alerting Profile will be alerted upon using the configurations made in the Problem Notification assigned to it. **If an alerting profile is not assigned to an associated Problem Notification, no alerts will be sent for that Alerting Profile.** Lastly, once all configurations have been set, there is a button that will send a test email to the configured recipients.

tiles.markdown:
# Maintenance Windows

Maintenance windows can be configured in Dynatrace to reduce alerting noise by suppressing problems and/or alerts during periods of maintenance. Maintenance windows also have a second purpose of excluding performance metrics measured within a maintenance period from regular baseline calculation. Maintenance window configuration is available to admins under **Settings > Maintenance windows > Monitoring, alerting and availability**. There are 3 major sections in maintenance window configuration: properties, schedule, and filters. 

Within the properties section, admins can configure the maintenance window name, description, type, and how the maintenance window will affect the behavior of Dynatrace. The maintenance window name and description should be descriptive and useful for identifying the purpose of the maintenance window. Maintenance type can hold one of two values; planned or unplanned. Planned maintenance windows are configured in advance while unplanned windows can be added retroactively to notify Dynatrace of unexpected downtimes that shouldn’t be factored into overall performance and availability baselines. The problem detection and alerting suppression option consists of a dropdown box that can hold one of the following values; detect problems and alert, detect problems but don’t alert, or disable problem detection during maintenance. This configuration is what determines how Dynatrace will treat anomalies, problems, and alerts during the maintenance period. Next, admins can choose to disable the execution of synthetic monitors that are within the scope of the maintenance window. This both prevents synthetic outages and avoids the usage of DEM units during periods of maintenance. 

The schedule section focuses on the timing of the maintenance window. First, set the recurrence schedule, starting with the dropdown box to select the recurrence type. This box can hold one of four values; once, daily, weekly, or monthly. Once selected the form will adapt to allow for specific configuration for the selected option. Next, set the start and end times for the maintenance window as well as the applicable time zone to be used. Next, if available, set the recurrence time frame by designating a start and end date and time.

The last section, filters, determines the scope of the maintenance window. Filters available include entity type, tags, management zones and specifically listed entities. Scope can be determined using multiple filters where separate filters use OR logic while each individual rule utilizes AND logic. Scope determines exactly which entities the maintenance window will apply to. If the scope is left un-configured a maintenance window will apply to the entire Dynatrace environment.

## Maintenance Window Troubleshooting Tip

Dynatrace has a built-in way to determine if a problem has occurred during a maintenance window. When on the problems page, on the left filter bar there is a section titled Context, as shown below. If the “Under maintenance” option is selected, problems opened within the scope and time frame of any configured maintenance windows will be displayed. An example is shown below. Problems are also labeled with “Problem occurred during maintenance window” to further distinguish them from non-maintenance problems. This helps to determine if maintenance windows are working as intended. 

Note: This troubleshooting trick will not work if anomaly detection is disabled during maintenance windows, as problems will not open with this configuration.
